igm. By establishing the conformity between those responses to past atrocities and the idea of "turning," Chung argues that the religious texts from the Old Testament encapsulating this idea (especially the Psalms of Repentance) are viable intellectual resources for dialogues among victims, perpetrators, bystanders, and their descendants in the discussion of guilt and responsibility, justice and reparation, remembrance and reconciliation. It is a great irony that after Nazi Germany sought to eliminate each and every single Jew within its reach, postwar Germans have depended on the Jewish device of repentance as a feasible way out of their unparalleled national catastrophe and unprecedented spiritual ruin.  afunded by Cornell University Library  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHistoriographyxMoral and ethical aspectszGermany. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xInfluence. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xMoral and ethical aspects. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xPublic opinion, German. 0aMemoryxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aPublic opinionzGermany. 0aRepentancexJudaism. 4aGERMAN STUDIES. 4aHistory. 4aJewish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aHolocaust, aftermath of the Holocaust, Nazi past, postwar German history, German Vergangenheinbewaltigung, German policy, historical reflection.2 aCornell University Libraryefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171253140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501712531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501712531/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL